    "narrative_summary": "Across the corpus, Adidas shows up in two clearly different visual modes. In earned exposure, the brand is embedded inside third-party sports footage: most concretely through the 2010 World Cup final\u2019s Adidas Jabulani match ball and the 2012 Team GB Olympic kit launch, where Adidas marks appear on athlete apparel. In owned exposure, Adidas is much more deliberate and legible: NMD and Yeezy are presented with controlled product hero shots, Samba is framed through repeated close-ups and trefoil iconography, and You Got This ends on unmistakable Adidas brand lockups.\n\nThe balance of evidence in this store leans toward owned presence being more explicit, emblematic, and visually dominant than earned presence. Event footage often shows Adidas as infrastructure inside the spectacle\u2014ball, uniform, or footwear\u2014while brand films center Adidas as the subject itself. By 2024, the corpus contains both modes side by side: the Euro 2024 final provides broad earned tournament context, while You Got This provides a crisp owned campaign signature. Overall, owned content delivers stronger brand salience; earned content delivers stronger cultural credibility and association with major global sporting stages.",
